'''Artistri Sud''' is a [[charitable organization|registered charity]] that provides entrepreneurship training to women artisans in [[Developing country|developing countries]]. The organization was founded in 2009 by [[Jennifer Lonergan]] and has implemented entrepreneurship training programs for women artisans and artisan groups in countries including [[Bolivia]], [[Chile]], [[Cambodia]], [[India]] and [[Zimbabwe]].<ref name="Gazette">Schwartz, Susan (March 5, 2016). ''[http://montrealgazette.com/life/applause-akiva-students-share-tall-tales-with-young-hospital-patients]'' Montreal Gazette.</ref><ref name="GlobalMontreal">Focus Montreal: Artistri Sud. ''[http://globalnews.ca/video/2560647/focus-montreal-artistri-sud]'' Global News.</ref>
{{Infobox organization | name = Artistri Sud | image = | type = Registered charity | founded = 2009 | location = Montreal, Quebec, Canada | founder = [[Jennifer Lonergan]] | website = [http://www.artistrisud.org/#sthash.NBHXH8q2.dpbs www.artistrisud.org] }}
== Operations == Based in [[Montreal]], Artistri Sud has built a following in [[Canada]] and abroad, using mainstream and [[social media]] platforms to raise awareness. The organization also hosts an annual fundraising event around [[International Women’s Day]] each year, recognizing local Montreal entrepreneurs for their work.<ref name="Design">"Tales of Triumph 2016" ''[http://designisyummy.com/tales-of-triumph/]'' Design Is Yummy.</ref>
The organization’s founder and executive director, [[Jennifer Lonergan]], is the organization's only paid employee. All other positions are filled by volunteers and interns. Artistri Sud has around 50 volunteers, and about 90% of them are women.
All donations made and grants received are used to fund the entrepreneurship training programs the organization implements in developing countries to empower women.
== History ==
=== Beginnings === Prior to launching the [[Nonprofit organization|nonprofit]], executive director Lonergan opened a retail store in 2008, Artistri Atelier Boutique. The idea was to support women craftspeople both in [[Canada]] and in the developing world by promoting and selling their work in the store.<ref name="Chatelaine">Friedman, Caroline (September 24, 2010). Coup de coeur Boutique Artistri''[http://blogues.chatelaine.com/blogue-bouffe/coup-de-coeur-boutique-artistri/2010/09/]'' Chatelaine.</ref><ref name="Zurbaine">September 24, 2010. Artistri - Les artizanes''[http://zurbaines.com/fr/plaisirs-zurbains/decoration/artistri/]'' Vos copines en ville - zurbaines.</ref><ref name="Empathic">Empathic Action Interview. ''[https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=njNJDV8lAZI]'' YouTube.</ref> The retail store is now closed.
=== Today === Today the nonprofit’s main activity is the implementation of its [[entrepreneurship]] training programs in the developing world, to empower women artisans to run their own micro-enterprises and earn a sustainable income to support themselves and their families.<ref name="Gazette" /><ref name="CBC">CBC News: Montreal - March 09, 2016. ''[http://www.cbc.ca/player/play/2685038087]'' CBC.</ref>
