{{multiple issues| {{notability|Television|date=September 2016}} {{refimprove|date=October 2018}} {{expert|date=October 2018}} }} {{Infobox television | show_name = First Business | image = FirstBusinesslogo.jpg | runtime = 30 minutes, inc. advertising | creator = | company = {{ubl|BizNet (1989-)|[[Weigel Broadcasting]] (2003-14)}} | executive_producer = Harvey Moshman (2008-2014) | presenter = {{ubl|Angela Miles|Chuck Coppola|Bill Moller}} | country = United States | network = [[television syndication|first-run syndication]] | picture_format = [[480i]] [[SDTV]] [[widescreen]] | first_aired = [[1989 in television|1989]] | last_aired = {{dts|2014|12|22}} | num_episodes = 260/year | website = [http://www.firstbusinessnews.com/ firstbusinessnews.com] |}}
'''''First Business''''' (full name '''First Business News''') was a [[television syndication|nationally syndicated]] financial news and analysis [[television program]], produced by First Business Network LLC, a [[subsidiary]] of [[Weigel Broadcasting]], in [[Chicago]]. Anchor [[Angela Miles]], reporters Chuck Coppola and Bill Moller, and executive producer Harvey Moshman brought viewers commentary from the floors of the [[Chicago Mercantile Exchange]] and the [[Chicago Board Options Exchange]], as well as from their studios in the [[West Loop]]. The program covered the financial and economic markets including [[equities]], [[Futures contract|futures]], [[option (finance)|options]], [[commodities]], [[foreign exchange market|foreign exchange]], and [[geo-political]] news.{{fact|date=October 2018}}
The program, which typically aired before local and national [[breakfast television|morning news]] timeslots, had been marginalized as those shows began to start earlier (as early as 4:00&nbsp;a.m.), with ''First Business'' often moved to lower-rated and lower-viewed [[graveyard slot]]s. The program's cancellation ended 47 years of Weigel Broadcasting and their flagship station [[WCIU-TV]] (channel 26) carrying and originating business-focused programming from Chicago.{{fact|date=October 2018}}
==Syndication== As of the fall 2011 season, the program was carried daily on more than 100 US [[broadcast television|broadcast stations]] and in outlets across 46 foreign countries. The stations included affiliates of [[American Broadcasting Company|ABC]], [[CBS]], [[NBC]], [[Fox Broadcasting Company|Fox]], [[The CW Television Network|The CW]], [[MyNetworkTV]], as well as independent stations. Air times varied, though the timeslots for the show in the majority of markets was 4:00am through 7:00am leading into early morning national newscasts or local morning newscasts. The only requirement the show enforced was that the program must air before the [[New York Stock Exchange|NYSE]] opening bell at 9:30am ET (except for Alaska or Hawaii, where time zones necessitated a post-opening bell airing). The show was syndicated by Weigel Broadcasting and sold by Edward. E. Finch & Company.{{fact|date=October 2018}}
==History== The ''First Business'' program was originally launched in 1989 by BizNet, the broadcast division of the [[US Chamber of Commerce]] in [[Washington, DC]].<ref name=rf>{{cite news|url=http://www.robertfeder.com/2014/11/17/closing-bell-tolls-for-first-business-news/|title=Closing bell tolls for ‘First Business News’ at Weigel Broadcasting|last=[[Robert Feder|Feder, Robert]]|date=17 November 2014|publisher=RobertFeder.com|accessdate=29 November 2014}}</ref> From its inception through its BizNet years with the US Chamber of Commerce, the First Business program production team was led by BizNet News Director Densil Allen.{{fact|date=October 2018}}
The production of First Business was later taken over from BizNet by [[CONUS Communications]], a joint venture of [[Viacom]] and [[Hubbard Broadcasting]], who would produce the program until 2003. Barton Eckert hosted the program from CONUS' bureau in Washington, DC, with his anchor segments being fed via satellite to CONUS' headquarters in St. Paul, Minnesota, where news packages acquired from CONUS' local member stations nationwide and other sources would be inserted into the program along with Eckert's anchor segments fed in from Washington, with the finished program being delivered via satellite to local stations from St. Paul every weekday.{{fact|date=October 2018}}
In 2003, Weigel Broadcasting took over the program and moved the show to Chicago. With the loss of affiliates for the show due to expanded local morning news, Weigel decided to shut down the program. First Business News last show was produced on December 22, 2014.<ref name=rf/>
